## Gap 2 — The 99.0% Figure Applies Only to Per-Packet Tier 2, Not Amortized Average

### What the gap is
After an epoch is established (one-time cost: 22.55 ms), each subsequent Tier 2 packet costs 0.075 ms — giving 99.0% per-packet reduction. However, if the epoch initiation cost (22.55 ms) is amortized over all packets in the epoch, the per-packet average is:
- At N=50: (22.55 + 49×0.075)/50 = **0.528 ms/packet** → **92.9% reduction**
- At N=100: (22.55 + 99×0.075)/100 = **0.300 ms/packet** → **95.9% reduction**

The original paper stated only 99.0% without clarifying that this is the Tier 2-only per-packet figure.

### Why it matters to a reviewer
> *"Your 99.0% is misleading. You must include the epoch handshake cost. The real amortized saving is much lower."*

### Fix Type
**Claim fix** (paper) + **Code output documentation**

### Fix Location 1 — Paper
**File:** [C:\Users\aloob\Downloads\Research Backup\simulation\results\novelty_proof_and_results.md](file:///Users/aloob/Downloads/Research%20Backup/simulation/results/novelty_proof_and_results.md)
**Section:** §4.1 — "Amortized Average Cost Per Packet" sub-table

**What was written:**
A dedicated sub-table with three rows:
```
| Tier 2 only (after epoch) | — | 0.075 ms | 99.0% |
| N = 50 packets            | — | 0.53 ms  | 92.9% |
| N = 100 packets           | — | 0.30 ms  | 95.9% |
```
With blockquote:
```
> [GAP 2 — BEST FIX: Two-number presentation]
> Two distinct figures are reported: (1) per-packet Tier 2 cost (99.0%) — the cost
> saving for each individual data packet after epoch establishment; (2) amortized
> average per packet including epoch initiation (92.9%–95.9% for N=50–100).
> Both figures are extraordinary and mutually reinforcing.
```

### Fix Location 2 — Simulation Code
**File:** [C:\Users\aloob\Downloads\Research Backup\simulation\sim_latency.m](file:///Users/aloob/Downloads/Research%20Backup/simulation/sim_latency.m)
**Lines:** 75–79

**What was written:**
```matlab
fprintf('  [NOTE] This %% applies to Tier 2 per-packet cost only.\n');
fprintf('  [NOTE] Amortized average at N=50:  (...)/50 = %.3f ms/packet\n', ...);
fprintf('  [NOTE] Amortized average at N=100: (...)/100 = %.3f ms/packet\n', ...);
```

### How it favours novelty
Having **two numbers** (99.0% per-packet AND 92.9%/95.9% amortized) is stronger than one number. A reviewer who tries to compute the amortized average finds it already disclosed and still extraordinary (92.9% at N=50). There is no "gotcha" moment. Both figures reinforce each other.

