## Gap 2 — 0.074×10⁶ Cycles Is Benchmark-Estimated, Not Measured

### What the gap is
The Tier 2 cycle count (0.074×10⁶ = HKDF ~4,000 + AES-256-GCM ~68,000 + overhead) comes from Intel AES-NI benchmark tables — not directly measured in MATLAB using `tic/toc` or hardware counters. The base paper competitor values (Lizard, RLizard, LEDAkem, Code-based HE) are from the published paper's own hardware measurements. The comparison mixes measured and benchmark-estimated values.

### Why it matters to a reviewer
> *"You compare directly measured competitor cycles against benchmark-estimated Tier 2 cycles. What if the real cycle count is 0.100×10⁶? Your 33× factor becomes 24×. You can't claim 33× with an estimate."*

### Fix Type
**Claim fix** (paper only — no code change to cycle values)

### Fix Location — Paper
**File:** [C:\Users\aloob\Downloads\Research Backup\simulation\results\novelty_proof_and_results.md](file:///Users/aloob/Downloads/Research%20Backup/simulation/results/novelty_proof_and_results.md)
**Section:** §4.3 — "Reduction Factor and Worst-Case Analysis" sub-table + Gap 2 blockquote

**What was written in the table:**
```
| Benchmark estimate (Intel AES-NI) | 0.074×10⁶ | ~33× vs Base | ~38× vs LEDAkem |
| Pessimistic case (+35% overhead)  | 0.100×10⁶ | ~24× vs Base | ~28× vs LEDAkem |
```

**What was written in the blockquote:**
```
> [GAP 2 — BEST FIX: Range claim, worst-case anchored]
> The Tier 2 cycle count (0.074×10⁶) is derived from Intel AES-NI benchmark
> tables — not directly MATLAB-measured. A pessimistic case (0.100×10⁶ — 35%
> higher, accounting for MATLAB overhead, memory allocation, and scheduling jitter)
> yields a reduction of ~24×, still the lowest cycle count of all methods in the
> table. The reduction claim is presented as a range: 24×–33× fewer clock cycles
> per packet. Even at the worst-case floor, the proposed scheme is lower-energy
